properties.hazard_detail: There is a small pot hole about here in the bike lane. If you bike this route, you will see it. It where the cyclist swerve.
Poor continuation of bike lane forcing cyclists wanting to ride straight through Carey into ast traffic traffic turning right onto Marigold.
Traffic moves faster than normal and the road is very narrow.
It's a big dip on a storm grate, just on the south east side of the intersection. It's too big to go through/over on your bike.

Bikes continuing south on Shelbourne are in conflict with traffic turning right (west) onto hillside avenue. Multiple conflicts occur and cyclists need to use extreme caution especially during peak traffic hours.

When trying to turn left onto Cadboro Bay Road from Cedar Hill Cross Road it is often hazardous because the traffic coming from the left is coming up hill and around the corner. The speed limit is 40 km, but many drivers go faster than that.  
The 40 km sign needs to be closer to the intersection a
Shelbourne is too narrow and busy. If you ride at the edge of the road, drivers often pass too closely. If you take up the lane, they get impatient.
Roadworks block the road
Construction crews building a house are parking their work vehicles in the bike lane. Happens frequently.
Pothole in the center of the road.

Uphill busy Northbound approach to stoplight. Road narrows on the uphill as you near the traffic light, and there is no way for a cyclist to get to either the side or the front of cars. Risk of being forced off road into ditch or hit by cars as they approach the light.  The road needs to be widened.

This block long section of Maddison Street is along the flattest and shortest route from Fairfield to UVIC/Oak Bay High/Shelbourne.  
It's been laid to waste by the City's neglect and its high manholes, dips and ruined surface put the city to shame!  
Flatten and pave it correctly, Victoria....
Southbound traffic may not stop for light due to high speed and poor visibility. Use extreme caution crossing road.
Traffic may not stop for light. Take extra caution!
Large pothole in the middle of a heavy bike use road. At night it is very dark and would pose a risk to riders.
Loose aggressive dogs

A delivery truck was parked in the bike lane. I signalled a lane change and, after shoulder checking, entered the full lane on Beatty Street between Robson and Georgia. A late-model luxury car overtook me, honked, and buzzed past, crossing the yellow line, then turned right at the next intersection.
loose aggressive dogs
Viaduct closed to traffic

crossing is a popular route for cyclists, however, given there is no way to cross during congested periods cyclists are forced to make a risky crossing unsetting drivers and exposing cyclists to danger of a collision with a vehicle. cyclist controlled light and/or signage required.
Construction in the area has caused vehicles to enter the bike lane.
Down hill track, then crossing a main road, poor visibility from left due to overhanging tree branches.  The hazard only exist when biking westwards.
The pavement is developing cracks and potholes that make it even more treacherous to ride on Shelbourne Street.
Very poor road to be riding on.  Lots of traffic,  no bike lanes.  Burnside Road is another accident waiting to happen.
Marked Graham St/Vancouver St bike route is difficult to follow across Bay St.  Crossing lights are available for pedestrians but not easily accessible by cyclists.
Blind curve. Several crashes I the past year. Please take curve under 18mph

When riding eastbound downhill towards Ash and needing to make a left traffic behind coming on fast -- needs some form of traffic calming. Bike lane abruptly ends at Ash and road is very narrow putting bikes in direct vehicle path right on the curve.

When headed soutbound on West Saanich towards the bike path that goes through the tunnel under the Pat Bay highway -- bikers must turn left across traffic via the crosswalk over the Island.  There is no left turn lane to go from the West Saanich Bike Path to the Royal Oak bike path -- dangerous.
This is, in my opinion as a Goose regular, the most dangerous crossing. Cars come down the road expecting to merge with the highway, and will often ignore the fact there's a crosswalk there.
Extremely Slippery! Polished concrete is insanely slick when wet. Especially coupled with the speeds usually carried into this corner. Please brake before entering and proceed with caution.

This is the short wooden bridge you cross before nearing the main Colwood intersection. In the summer and dry days, it's fine, but in the winter the bridge frosts over, making it *extremely* slippery. I've heard of several accidents, a friend broke her hip crashing here, and crashed 2x myself.
Constant dangers with parked cars coming in and out.
HAULTRAIN CROSSES COOK. 4 LANES OF HEAVY TRAFFIC AND THERE  IS NO WAY TO STOP TRAFFIC OTHER THAN RISK A QUICK CROSSING OR AT THE GRACE OF A DRIVER(S)
People were waiting for the bus on the bike lane.
People waiting for a bus a blocking the bike lane
Potholes and ruts
Many drivers run this 4way especially in the am. Also ignore cyclists that have stopped and entering intersection. Kids use this intersection frequently
Bad 4way stop. Drivers often run intersection. Stop signs not well placed esp for drivers unfamiliar w area.
Curb juts out into side Lane at end of parking here. Not marked  for night or low light conditions. Very hazardous easy to hit obstacle.
This Island may be designed to slow traffic but it narrows passage for cyclists. Drivers also speed around this corner and limited visibility.
Vehicles drive too fast down this residential street on route to oak bay village. Should be 40 or less.
Many drivers exceed 70 km/h on the stretch. Very hazardous. Lots of students and dog walkers here. Also many drivers exit rec centre into traffic here.

Construction barricades used creating extremely tight turns and unnecessarily narrow passageways for bikes and pedestrians.  Congestion on Bridge westbound widens with new bike lane but then lane is filled with fencing squeezing cyclists back into main traffic.   Extremely hazardous conditions!
The road at the end of Pembroke dead-ends. So, the many cycling commuters take the sidewalk through to Fernwood, and back.
Dirty road, water and mud
Cyclist (coming from east) can be hard to see in the morning, because of the sunrise. Almost got T-bone twice.
Some drivers uses this street as a shortcut. It's is quite narrow, with cars parked on both sides of the street. Some drivers will pass a few feets from cyclist.
It is common for drivers to do a right turn when the light is red (to let cyclist and pedestrian cross the road). Some will even do a rolling stop without looking for incomming cyclists.
Some drivers will circumvent the bike only blockade. The same drivers that will, speed and pass a few feet from you.

Vehicles turning right will crowd the bike lane, especially when stopped for the red light. They tend not to look to the right, instead looking left for the oncoming traffic. Also, motorcyclists will run the bike lane to make the right turn, sometimes squeezing past cyclists.
Power pole is in the bike lane

We live a 5 minute walk from Granville Island. There is one path on this south side seawall with no separation between pedestrians and bicyclists. There are many blind corners as the walkway winds along the water. Bikes go too fast. People are not paying attention. Young children are running about.
This intersection is a hot-spot for bike/vehicle incidents.  Be careful when crossing Wale Road at this location.  Both vehicle drivers and Cyclists can be at fault here.

When traffic is backed up there is potential that a vehicle will turn into Adams Place.  As the vehicle is turning left across two lanes there is potential that a cyclist cannot see the vehicle.  Be careful going down this hill towards sooke intersection.

No bike lane northbound during overpass construction. Uphill creates greater speed differential between bicycles and cars, exacerbating issue of having to share lane. Option to cross on sidewalk against traffic and cross back on other side of overpass.
Nortbound, just as bike lane resumes after construction.
Driver's do not know how to use 4-way stop when cyclists approach intersection. Also, the section between Douglas and Lougheed is dangerous due to cars turning on and off of Gilmore.
Sharp 180 degrees turn of the bike path does not allow bikes to cross safely: make sure no one is coming the other way
Flying golf balls
Difficult for merging vehicles coming from underpass to see bicycle riders in cycling lane.  Witnessed an automobile accident in this location.
The current construction of Johnson Street bridge is dangerous to cyclists, poor signage, a bike lane that abruptly ends.
Blind crossing near high traffic area

This is an intersection of the Goose which drivers do not pay enough attention to. This is partly due to design and partly due to inadequate signage.
On the day in question, the driver cruised right through the stop sign, oblivious. I know a woman was hit here recently.

the new piece of Esquimalt Rd is poorly signed for cyclists, in both directions. There is a piece of westbound bike lane that ends after a few feet, forcing you to suddenly merge with cars. For eastbound cyclists, it is very confusing, so use caution, especially in the dark &/or rain.
Driver veered into bikelane
Very rough, uneven pavement in front of the WRPS station.  Forces road bikes/anyone with skinny tires far into the lane of traffic between Weber St. and Marsland Drive.  Danger!!!

This crosswalk (which is a part of the bike path) is a bit dangerous. Partially due to visibility (plant growth-  i.e. trees and blackberry bushes), but also due to the fact that drivers (mostly those headed downhill) do not wish to stop at the (poorly) marked crosswalk.
Walkway/cycle path between Eric Rd. and Beam Crescent is lined by a high hedge on the north side, restricting visibility as one exits onto Beam Crescent.
Contractor vehicle parked in the bike lane.
Contractor van and police cruiser parked in the bike lane.

Many leaves in the bike lane, and deep puddles.

This is a picture from the following morning (when most of the puddles were gone): http://i.imgur.com/VLaMaxN.jpg?1

The vast majority of drivers turning right from the circle onto M St NW do not yield to cyclists in the bike lane. The drivers turning right illegally from the center lane don't usually yield to anyone.

RIDE ON SIDEWALK ON MONTLAKE BRIDGE
Bridge surface is metal grating that, especially when wet, is terrifyingly slippery.  No signage.

Drivers outside the Trader Joe's frequently merge into the bike lane without looking while attempting to parallel park or enter/exit the parking garage.   Also, huge door hazard here.   Suggest merging with traffic and avoiding the bike lane altogether.
Directly on the southbound bike lane when crossing Marine
Vehicles frequently use the bike lane as a turning lane. This happens daily.
Bike lane ends with no accommodation for cyclists on a busy road with merging traffic
Bike wheel got caught in train track that goes diagonally across the road, causing bike to slide sideways into oncoming traffic.

This is a section of road in between streetlights and has very poor visibility at night. It's near a corner too, and I think there are manhole covers, so it's not a straightforward path and it's hard to see.  Would be a good place to put a new lamp post!
Car parked in the bike lane on Pine. Driver talking on this cell phone.

The bike lane ends for 1 block in both directions on Pacific Blvd between Hornby and Howe street. The only way to cycle on Pacific here is to merge into traffic for this block until the bike lane resumes. Traffic is heavy and fast moving here especially during rush hour.
Repaving at train crossing left a lip of about 5 cm in south bound shoulder that can catch a front wheel and cause a crash

Lack of road marking to advise high speed traffic turning right unto Springbrook Road that bike lane proceeds thru the intersection.   Should be hashmarks put down to show continuity of bike lane thru that intersection
Double tracks, oblique crossing

Overpass on 208th Ave over Hwy #1 has bike path directing cyclists unto a sidewalk which is 15 cm  above roadway, windy environment that can cause cyclist to be blown back unto roadway. Conflicts with pedestrian traffic.
Narrow overpass, heavy traffic, bike path on sidewalk which is elevated above roadbed, windy
Southbound bike lane on a blind curve.  High traffic speed.  Motorists cut the corner drifting into bike lane and potential of a cyclist being hit from behind.

Due to the construction of the new Amercan Ambasy a constructionroad has been added. The cyclepath is interrupted with an elavation in the road and the continuation of the cyclepath is not vissible from your entry point at that junction. Also trafficflow is from the constructionsite towards the N44.
Sand on roadservice and poor visibility in the corners
Sand on road
Giant bridge support post in the middle of the trail. Near misses here with other cyclists and pedestrians all the time.
Bike lanes end abruptly as the road narrows at train track. You should plan to ride on the sidewalk or ride further into the lane to ensure you have adequate space.
Cyclists frequently disregard stop signs causing dangerous motor vehicle behaviours.

Poorly placed banana bars at entrance to bikeway.
BCC refuses to move as recommended to improve safety.

Road is quite narrow, heavy traffic, drivers not willing to slow down.
There is, unfortunately, no alternative route for cyclist.
Rallye du Valais - Lots of race cars speeding around all day & road closure to bikes.

Bikeway runs straight into a BBQ rotunda.
Please take care at night.
Island does not allow for cyclists or wheelchairs to cross smoothly.   Crossing would be safer and easier with a curb cut in this island.
Missing a north/south designated bike route near Edmonton Trail or 6 St NE that would connect the communities of Renfrew and the central business district.
Overpass, high congestion, poor driver behavior

Bridge over creek is a collection point for debris which is otherwise washed off the rest of the trail by rain. While it's part of a trail that is generally in good shape, this bridge is always covered with dirt and gravel and frequently has broken glass. since I started commuting in April 2014
Both sides of Mississippi are in bad shape at gutters but NE corner of intersection is crumbling and broken sidewalk curb ramp.  Crossing Broadway be prepared for bumpy asphalt and heavy traffic.
No bike lanes
Drainage culvert opens directly into roadway parallel with direction of travel without any grate or signage warning of it.
Bike lane striped to the right of a right turn only lane without using bike signals.
Storm grate is parallel to road.  Can make for a bad day if your tire drops into the slat.
Multiple new potholes have opened up along Pear St, some are hard to see.
Right lane is forced to turn right, uphill, heavy and fast traffic.

It is always hard to see south up Yukon when going through this intersection. I also see cyclists frequently blow through the stop signs here. A flashing yellow for motorists on Yukon or lights would are warranted here.

The blinking hand lasts a long time on 10th Ave, so it is hard to know when it is safe to enter this large intersection on bike (there is no countdown). A countdown might help traffic - in eve. rush hour there is ALWAYS a vehicle stuck in the intersection on a red light, heading south on Cambie.
Bikepath under Stewart Rd/Wardell St is poorly aligned and too narrow to allow for easy passing.
Vehicles driving in the bike lane to turn left from Gordon Head Rd to McKenzie Ave.
Vehicles frequently use the bike lane here to drive through, either to turn right or go straight.

Bitumen surface in roundabout is separating and opening up large cracks in the pavement making it dangerous for cyclists at the point where they are leaning their bikes over to go round the bend in the roundabout.
About 1 foot in diameter but quite deep so hazardous to bikes (especially in the dark!)
Big potholes after round-abouts.  Bad route for bikes in general due to large cracks and potholes on 61st from Beach Dr to Admiral Way.
Extreme amounts of pedestrians walking with no regard to cyclists and no separate cycling lanes.
shoulder narrows to nothing between colony farm and pitt river road
Construction zone repaving the road.
Big pothole just as the bike lane moves over to accommodate additional lane
Bike lane inexplicably ends without warning for 15 meters then returns again.
Not a bike friendly area. Shipping containers sandwich in riders with rough roads and high traffic volume.
Bike lanes on bridge frosted & icy. Possibly not salted/brined unlike the roadway.
Can't get over to bike lane during traffic
Wildlife. Deer clustered on the road.
Vehicle parked in left turn bike lane
Loose gravel covering bikeway from unsealed driveway access into rail yards.

It's a busy intersection where traffic headed for the commercial strip on Old Airport Road blends with traffic headed for Kam Lake. Drivers resist/ignore cyclists who signal intention to cross from the kerb lane to the south-bound lane.
On the west side of the tracks there's a 10" wooden strip which becomes as slick as ice when wet.
Car door opening on bike traffic. Not enough room for 2 lanes of cars + bikes. Major conflict area that needs to be addressed.

Driver did not wait for me to cross the Trent River overpass.  I was half way across and the speeding car passed me heading into oncoming traffic.  I needed to stop and move over to ensure the car did get past without a collision.
Bikes heading south on Foul Bay have conflict with cars / buses turning west onto Lansdowne rd.  Turning lane and bike lane merge and it is confusing where bikes should go to get out of the way.

Morning commute traffic backs up and bikes conflict with cars. Only an issue between 8:30-9:30am. Lack of communication + coordination with bikes and vehicles. Hopefully a bike lane on McGill would solve this issue.

People driving cars are not looking for cyclists or yielding at this intersection causing several close calls for right hooks (west bound) in particular. Preventative education for people on bikes and in cars is available through the Wisconsin Bike Fed. http://wisconsinbikefed.org/wp-content/uploads

Road construction with limited to no shoulder and excessive vehicle speeds.
Greendale to Masterson Station Park

Bike Lane disappears for 1 block (both directions) on McKenzie.

Traffic squeezes bikes into curb.

No signs.
Boys and Girls Club of Victoria donation truck parked in the bike lane.
Vehicle parked in the bike lane
Pothole on apex of bikelane swept path on left hand turn from Sylvan Rd (west) to Land St (north).  Pothole has had ineffective treatment.

I commute over the bridge every day and often there are oblivious pedestrians walking in the north-bound cycling lane wearing headphones and unable to hear a bell. Once or twice there have been groups of people with strollers reluctant to move because they thought bikes shouldn't be there.

Carrall Street bikeway southbound merges at intersection with Keefer street. There is a high vegetation in median between bike path and vehicle lane just before they  merge, that causes poor visibility and makes left hand turns for cyclists difficult to communicate.

The designated bike route from Union to Adanac jogs at Vernon drive. Stop signs are on Union & Adanac. There is significant vehicle traffic on Vernon taking a short cut through residential neighbourhood. Stop signs should be on Vernon as well.

Tall grasses in parklet on southeast corner of intersection obscure the view of the westbound bike path for drivers exit ramp from Cambie Bridge to 6th Avenue east. Drivers look west for right on red (eastward) and miss westbound cyclists.  There should be no right on red here!
Shoulder of SW Marine Dr was covered in snow and ice, while roadway was clear. Also, extremely heavy traffic due to construction.
Curb let downs at intersection of Spirit Trail and Lloyd Ave are narrower than marked Spirit Trail crossing
rough strip of asphalt across Spirit Trail
parking sign post bent in over the Spirit Trail
crosswalk is dark and not well lit. Cars are going at least 20 over the speed limit and don't slow down for peds. You risk your life crossing here
Construction
On sidewalk and road
rush hour out of the downtown is often so tight to the curb to be impassible by bike.  there is no bike lane.  rubbing will be common occurance
pothole in the southbound right lane on shelbourne, right where cyclists are riding.
2 parked cars on the bikeway/footpath
(Very low) asphalt curb and sidewalk, not very visible at all to road users on 232nd SB in bend to right just before reaching Kanaka Way intersection.
Curb is only semi dropped at intersection with Bridgeman Ave
Cyclists speed through stop sign at blind corner.
drivers run this 4-way stop frequently, especially along Cranmore.
Terrible intersection for visibility and drivers not stopping or seeing cyclists. Some don't realize musgrave is thru street here. No bike lanes. Time for lights or roundabout!

The two crosswalks through this park section have textured or stamped surface.  The surface is seperating from the ashphalt right in the bike lane creating a dangerous groove for road bikes with narrow wheels.  I also crashed when hitting this.
Bike lane crossing many times overlooked by car drivers. Near misses on daily basis.
It's too narrow here, hard to bike up with cars passing you over the speed limit and too close!
Cars don't always stop and look for bicycles before making left turns without a light. Often they will blindly follow car in front of them.
Lane is too narrow here. Cars often attempt dangerous passes.
new traffic pattern forces north bound traffic into bike lane..very hazardous for cyclists. This is a new change to accommodate a bike lane, but it is even more dangerous for cyclists than before.
Shit ton of glass in road
Potholes in the shoulder heading north, on the south side of the intersection on Foul Bay Rd.
Potholes and general road surface make riding this section of Shelbourne very unpleasant, especially when its raining.

The marker cones for the construction force bike riders out into the traffic lane for a couple hundred yards here. Very risky because all the traffic is in a rush for the ferries.

Dangerous multilane road crossing required for cyclists. All drivers are rushing to get into a fare booth and not expecting bikes to be crossing the road.http://www.vubblepop.com/canadas-doing-a-pretty-terrible-job-of-honouring-its-veterans/

Watch for small landscaping pebbles in the bike lane.  They are about 1 to 2 inches in diameter coming from 8120 Granville Ave.  I have kicked them off the road in the past but they keep coming back.  It's an ongoing problem.
